The propensity of being treated is very difference between the treatment and control groups. For matching/weighting, we want these to be similar! The log odds scale shows that there is some overlap but these groups have different propensities of treatment.

  1. Conduct 1:1 nearest-neighbor matching on the log odds of the propensity score. Use bal.plot() to compare the overall propensity score distributions. Do once without replacement and once with replacement. Why do you think there’s a difference? Try to figure it out. Estimate the ATT for each assumption (i.e., with or without replacement). If you achieve good overall balance on the propensity score, try checking individual covariate balance using love.plot().
ps_norep <- matchit(treat ~ black + hisp + nodegr + married + u74 + u75 + age + educ + re74 + re75 + 
            age^2 + educ^2 + re74^2 + re75^2, 
            data = d, 
            estimand = "ATT", 
            replace = FALSE)

ps_norep_df <- match.data(ps_norep)

lm(re78 ~ treat, 
   data = ps_norep_df, 
   weights = weights)

## Call:
## lm(formula = re78 ~ treat, data = ps_norep_df, weights = weights)

##      10.262       -4.286
ps_rep <- matchit(treat ~ black + hisp + nodegr + married + u74 + u75 + age + educ + re74 + re75 + 
            age^2 + educ^2 + re74^2 + re75^2, 
            data = d, 
            estimand = "ATT", 
            replace = TRUE)

ps_rep_df <- match.data(ps_rep)

lm(re78 ~ treat, 
   data = ps_rep_df, 
   weights = weights)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = re78 ~ treat, data = ps_rep_df, weights = weights)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        treat  
##      6.7443      -0.7679

It seems that if we allow the matching process to use the same cases multiple times (i.e., replace), then we et a better estimate of the effect of the treatment (closer to an actual gain of money adjusting for all covariates).

bal.plot(ps_norep, 
         which = "both", 
         type = "density", 
         var.name = "distance") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

bal.plot(ps_rep, 
         which = "both", 
         type = "density", 
         var.name = "distance") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

We can see quite clearly that in the no-replace model, there is no meaningful balance in the model covariates while the replacement model gets us much closer to covariate balance.
